    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Eugenicists like Francis Galton and Charles Davenport employed a range of discredited methods to justify their claims. They often cited the work of 19th-century anthropologists like Carl Linnaeus, who categorized humans into distinct racial groups based on physical characteristics. They claimed that skull shape, size, and other cranial features were indicative of intelligence, with supposedly \"more advanced\" skulls belonging to superior racial groups. For example, they argued that the \"Mongoloid\" skull shape, common in East Asian populations, was associated with inferior intelligence and moral character.\n\nThey also relied on the concept of \"hereditary degeneracy,\" which posited that certain physical traits, such as epilepsy or mental illness, were inherited and linked to lower social status. Eugenicists like Davenport claimed that these traits were more prevalent in certain racial groups, further reinforcing their notion of racial hierarchy.\n\nAdditionally, they invoked the idea of \"eugenics\" – the supposed idea that certain traits, like intelligence or physical strength, could be inherited and improved through selective breeding. They advocated for policies like forced sterilization and immigration restrictions to \"purify\" the gene pool and maintain racial hierarchies.\n\nKeep in mind that these claims were based on",
